  dialogue:
    waystones:
    - key: sunfield-meadow
      text: Walk gently. The meadow fed them, too, and they are under it.
    - key: bramble-hedgerows
      text: The stone does not grow back. Take it like you mean it.
    - key: old-growth-wood
      text: These roots drink deeper than you will ever dig. Let them.
    - key: silverrun-river
      text: The river keeps no ledger. Count what you take, for it will not.
    verses:
    - key: sunfield-meadow
      text: What you carry is borrowed. Set some down, and see what follows you home.
    - key: bramble-hedgerows
      text: "Sweetness kept, stone made bright \u2014 show the hedge what the taking
        taught you."
    - key: old-growth-wood
      text: Wood made useful, and one bone of what came before. The grove would hold
        it again.
    - key: silverrun-river
      text: Of all you pulled from the water, the river asks the finest back. It
        knows you have it.
    provisioner:
    - id: prov-01
      trigger: first-visit
      line: Sell me nothing you would weep to lose. I do not give refunds, and the
        land does not either.
    - id: prov-02
      trigger: after-migration
      line: The last warden asked fewer questions. Hm. Perhaps that was the trouble.
    migrationVignette:
    - The camp folds. The land exhales.
    - What you gave, it keeps.
    insectPlates:
    - key: stags-herald
      text: Antlers on a beetle no longer than your thumb. It fought something once,
        or meant to. The drawing is all I keep; the meadow keeps the rest.
    - key: silver-skimmer
      text: It held the one reach of river all afternoon and let me sketch it, wings
        still. The river fed its kind ten thousand years. I gave the page my hand
        and gave the water back its guest.
    - key: those-who-sow
      text: They carry the flowers from field to field without being asked, and have
        longer than we have. Whoever tends this place, it is not only us. I drew
        them, and let them go on.
